<subSubSection id="6D837C851033FFACDBE2FDB048312888" pageId="22" pageNumber="123" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="25262F0E1033FFACDBE2FDB048312888" blockId="22.[151,1437,151,933]" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1033FFACDBE2FDB04D012838" bold="true" box="[199,308,763,789]" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">Remarks</emphasis>
. Because the 
<typeStatus id="FA2291AC1033FFACDAFCFDB04E0E2838" box="[473,571,763,789]" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">holotype</typeStatus>
female of 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1033FFACD999FDB04F622838" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[700,855,763,789]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="malayanus">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1033FFACD999FDB04F622838" box="[700,855,763,789]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">A. malayanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is slightly compressed by cover slip pressure, the width of the head and pronotum have been changed slightly. It is very similar to 
<taxonomicName id="E299548D1033FFACDF3DFC5448CF2814" authorityName="Okajima &amp; Masumoto" authorityYear="2022" box="[1048,1274,799,825]" class="Insecta" family="Phlaeothripidae" genus="Asianthrips" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="123" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bamboosielloides">
<emphasis id="17EDF31C1033FFACDF3DFC5448CF2814" box="[1048,1274,799,825]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">A. bamboosielloides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry id="5D8E6F9E1033FFACDE18FC5449A92814" box="[1341,1436,799,825]" name="Vietnam" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">Vietnam</collectingCountry>
in having the very short maxillary stylets which are scarcely retracted to the basal collar of head, but the latter species is quite dissimilar in the yellow abdomen. One micropterous female (
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B1033FFACD8C8FC2C487528AC" box="[1005,1088,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–22" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1805,1829]" captionTargetBox="[158,1424,181,1782]" captionTargetId="figure-17@5.[158,1430,181,1782]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–22. Asianthrips species. A. magnus, 11–12; (11) Female (mac); (12) Female (mic). A. malayanus, 13–14; (13), Female (mac); (14) Non-paratypic female (mic). A. nobilis, 15–16; (15) Female (mac); (16) Female (mic). A. orientalis, 17–18; (17) Female (mac); (18) Male (mic). A. pallens, 19–20; (19) Female (mac); (20) Male (mic). A. parvinotus, 21–22; (21) Female (mac); (22) Male, non-paratype (mic)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404870" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404870/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">Figs 14</figureCitation>
&amp; 
<figureCitation id="BDA2338B1033FFACDF47FC2C484A28AC" box="[1122,1151,871,897]" captionStart="FIGURES 88–93" captionStartId="21.[151,264,1887,1911]" captionTargetBox="[230,1359,273,1864]" captionTargetId="figure-76@21.[229,1359,273,1864]" captionTargetPageId="21" captionText="FIGURES 88–93. Asianthrips malayanus, sp. n., female. (88) Head–pelta (mac); (89) Head–pelta (mic); (90) Antenna (mac); (91) Mesopresternum (mac); (92) Tergites II–III(mac); (93) Tube (mac)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6404904" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6404904/files/figure.png" pageId="22" pageNumber="123">89</figureCitation>
) listed as a non-paratypic specimen is a little damaged, and is possibly a microptera of the same species.
</paragraph>
